segments.text: History of College Station, Mr. J.O.
Mr. White, where were you born?
Why were you born on Kyle Field?
Because it was an experiment farm and it had houses on it.
Did your parents work for the experiment farm?
Were you born in the house?
Were there any hospitals at that time that you could have gone to?
I don't know who she was.
Was that the normal way, the kids?
In these houses that were on what is presently Kyle Field?
OK. Where were your parents from?
They were born in Brazos County?
Were they associated with the cotton plantations?
No, my mother was a domestic.
And my father worked at the experiment, you know.
What did he do at the cotton experiment station?
Well, we would cultivate it, etc.,
The cotton was planted behind the houses, is that right?
And he would go out and cultivate the cotton?
And did he and other men pick it, or did they have some other kind of?
So they were just trying out different things.
Different insects, et cetera, and all of that.
How long have your relatives lived in this area?
Have they lived here for a long time?
Ever since I've been launching, I have to remember.
Were maybe some of your relatives, great-grandparents, were they slaves on plantations that were around here?
She wasn't born in this country.
No, no, it's in my nose and my cheekbones and things.
It's not like the average black person.
That's what I was talking about.
So she came from India to Brazos County?
I don't know anything about it.
Your father was born in India?
But your mother's family had lived here.
Did your mother ever talk about your family extending back before the Civil War?
But my grandmother, she would tell me about
She was in the school system over there.
And she would tell you about... Well, how did she come to live in Texas?
Well, if I make no mistake, I believe she told me that somebody from the States...
told them that money was growing on trees.
And they were referring to cotton.
Did your grandmother know it, that they were talking about cotton?
And did she meet your grandfather here?
How many brothers and sisters do you have?
She lives in Inwood, Long Island, New York, and I haven't seen her since 1945 when I was discharged in New York.
Oh, I bet that's sad, not seeing your...
Can you tell me what it was like to grow up?
Apparently you must have lived on...
in this house on Kyle Field.
And can you tell me what it was like to grow up on the A&M campus?
Well, it was a great life.
I don't know anything about no depression.
Didn't have... Well, it was a depression, but I didn't know anything about it.
I would go to the dining hall and eat.
I'd go to the hospital and eat.
See, in that day and time, the Caucasian people, they didn't eat chicken wings, chicken livers, chicken necks.
And all of that would be put in the garbage, you see.
would confiscate that and save it, and they would take it down to Navasota to her father.
This was where they could survive during the Depression.
So you would take food from the college and take it to your folks, your grandparents.
The house that you grew up in, at first, did it have electricity?
What did you use in place of electricity?
There wasn't any running water in the house?
You had to go get it.
and the largest tin tub you could get.
Yes, that's what we would bathe in.
What kind of chores did you do when you were growing up?
Well, I found out large enough to have more lawns, play with Howard Hughes, Howard Hedge, George Wren, Bug Mouser,
These are all boys growing up on the campus?
When you say mow lawns, did you mow lawns on the A&M campus?
With a hand mower, not an electric mower.
Yeah, those are a lot more difficult.
Where did you go to school?
Oh, you went to the elementary school and Brian?
Used to have to ride a trolley.
Some of the neighbors you couldn't catch on with.
Did the other boys also go to school there, too?
Well, the black boys and the boys you were mentioning just a minute ago?
No, they was white boys, the one I was mentioning.
Why didn't you go to consolidated?
A Negro and white wasn't attending the same school.
Was there a Negro school in Bryan that you went to?
There used to be a Negro school down there by this church.
There was a Negro school there.
When was that, before you went to school?
Well, I can't say it was established, but elementary school, that's where I went.
That's where you went when you were in elementary school?
So right here where Washington Chapel is, there was a- Just this side of Washington Chapel.
There was a black elementary school.
Where did the students come from?
All over, all up in Boyce Flat and all up here on the other side of it, on Culpeper Plaza.
There used to be a lot of black houses over here.
Black families all over on the Wildland Road.
They all went to that one-room school.
And you were not allowed to go to the school, the consolidated school that was started on the A&M campus?
Was that something that, was it something that bothered you then?
It didn't bother me because I was raised around whites all my life and really, I really didn't consider myself a
That's the way it should be.
Because you take Preston Bolden, Frank Bolden, Dean Winkle's boys, and, uh... Bob Malden.
A.C. Lewis, Billy Lewis, Frank Brown, Jr. All of those people were Caucasians.
Charlie Harris, his father was head of the laundry.
Frank Brown, Jr., his daddy was head of the electrical department, head electrician on A&M College.
Billy and A.C. Lewis, their father was the head of the plumbing department on the campus.
Keith Langford, his father was the first mayor A&M College had.
People who lived in the community?
They were humans, but they were still Caucasian.
I didn't go to school with them.
Holland, his father was a foreman on the railroad track.
On Welburn, is it located where it is today?
Do you know where it's located today?
You know where Fish Richard's restaurant is?
Going down, just opposite the college, there's a cement plant or something down there.
Do you feel like that you got an adequate education?
Were the teachers that you had, were they Negro or did you have white teachers?
What did you do if somebody was sick?
Where did you go if someone in your family was sick?
Was there any kind of a Negro community?
What did the Negro people do for living around this area?
There's a lot of them older than me that was born on A&M College.
A lot of them were born on A&M College?
And others, I can't recall, offhand.
OK. Was there any kind of a group?
Did you ever get together to do activities together?
We used to play ball right back at Consolidated School when it was on the campus.
Did you play against other teams?
Or just boys getting together to play?
We played against the wave, going on the campus.
They'd come out down here and we'd play ball.
And how important was the church?
Was there a church that you attended, your family?
Where the school was, near the school?
And then there was St. Matthew's.
Did y'all attend church a lot?
She used to work for Mrs. Thomas, Mrs. Bryson,
Mrs. Barrett, Mrs. Jackie Walker, she raised Johnny Walker Knox Jr. And the Mayfields.
Apparently on campus there were these houses.
Did she work for people that lived on campus?
Do you remember what it looked like, where the houses were located on the campus?
I can go in there and point out where each house used to be.
Can you tell me the approximate location where these houses were?
Well, by me not being too familiar with the campus now, all that where the Stuluk Center is, houses was there.
start at Wilburn Road, come on up by the stadium, on around, just everywhere.
The faculty and some Army personnel, Colonel George F. Moore, used to stay opposite Guyon Hall.
Dr. Freps, Dr. J.J. Tobinhouse, A.B.
Were there houses at Northgate on the campus still or across?
Do you remember when these houses and the house that you lived in, do you remember when they were moved off campus or what happened to them?
Well, I remember but I don't recall the year.
Because when I left, after I came out of high school, Clark, Coleson,
and his brother Jim and old man Colson, they had a triple A building down there, a long cabin just below Kyle Field before you get off the campus.
There was a lot of trees around there.
The Colson lived just inside on the campus, just outside on the campus.
Mr. Fleming lived, I recall his initial, Colonel Todd lived down there, Mrs. Todd, Fletcher, Schultz, Littles, Langfoot, Bryson, Lancaster, McNew,
These are people who lived off campus in the little community?
But do you remember when the houses were moved off or why the houses that were on campus?
When you were growing up, can you describe what College Station looked like to me?
Well, it's a very pretty place.
All those live oak trees, I remember when a lot of them was plagued, or was planted.
And they had the gardeners going around taking care of them.
They stayed right across from Guyon Hall.
And I just can't recall all of the names.
Oh, no, you've given me plenty.
Wallen Sr. was a very nice man.
I remember once the Aggie was coming from, I believe, SMU or TCU by train.
And Teal and I got up and rode his sister's bicycle, Lily Mae, and his bicycle down to the station.
And somebody told Dr. Walden about it.
And so we got what was coming to us.
And you got in trouble, too?
Well, sure, I got in trouble, too.
Dr. Morris was one of the kindest men.
Miss Claygon, she was more mouth than anything.
Gold, had a heart of gold.
I used to work for Mr. Harry Boyer.
Joe E. Davis, he's become the king.
King, Sergeant Daniel, and so many others.
Well, when you were growing up, what did it look like on this part of the city at Eastgate?
And who owned it, or who lived here?
There was a black family that lived up on that hill.
Down here where the light is,
They formed, and it's plant cotton.
All along here, this... How would you spell vulva?
So this area was cotton farmland?
And this was just a two-lane gravel road?
What was the area at, I guess, Southgate like?
All those houses on the left point?
Well, Frank Double Boy on that, he had rent houses, shotgun rent houses for blacks.
I used to live over there.
About what year did he have those?
Right over where all these nice homes are.
Going back toward the Kyle Field, I came back here and a school had been built up there.
Just the other side of that, Mr. Bill Sparks and Hersha Burgess, they developed that.
And Mr. Hensley and his brother, they built some homes up there right beside the highway.
Mr. Burgess built a big house back there.
And I think Mr. Sparks built a house back there.
I think I remember reading that.
At Westgate, that was where the train station was.
Right, right across from over there.
The creamery used to be there.
Do you happen to remember the college zoo?
There was a zoo there in the 20s.
I thought that was interesting that they had a zoo.
That's how I had heard about it.
Well, I used to go there fishing.
Now we call them white putch.
Did you have the stores or anything developed when you were growing up?
Mr. Sparks and Jeff Casey had a drugstore up there.
Dr. Lipscomb used to work for Mr. Casey and Mr. Spock.
He built a drugstore across the street.
Luke and Charlie had a grocery store.
And the Boyds always had on that land up there.
And built a cleaning and pressing shop.
And that's this church up there.
I think the minister was named Reverend Brown.
But there were very few men.
Used to raise cotton all out there.
You know where the theater is?
Back that way, that was the Boyettes.
Oh, I know what you're talking about.
I think you mentioned earlier Boyette Flats, is that right?
That's Upper Borough where a whole lot of apartments up there.
There's apartments now in that area?
Is that, was that an area, Boyette Flats, what was there?
Shotgunning out with blacks living in them.
Well, this is as long as I can remember up until the 30s.
Because I know a lot of kids were born up there.
So past Northgate area and where the apartment complexes are now is an area that was called Rear Flats.
And now we're on shotgun houses for black families.
And these black families worked on A&M campus.
Roland Columbus, Albert Pierce, and that group, another back group.
Roland Columbus was the second in command to the Lewis plumbers.
He knew more about the campus plumbing on the campus than anybody.
And he lived like at University in Texas?
She lived over there somewhere on College Hills, I think.
Well, what I was interested in is
Were the black people that lived here, the Negro community that developed, had they lived here for a long time in Brazos County?
Do you think maybe they had lived here before the Civil War?
Well, I see along the Brazos River there were cotton plantations, and I was wondering maybe if somewhere...
They migrated in here, getting better paying jobs.
We had been here all our lives.
Well newcomers, black or white or both?
And they were coming because of the university to work there?
Across the river, out at Rowan Chapel, just everywhere.
Okay, I was just curious on how people started living here before A&M, I guess, was built.
Ever since I've been old enough to remember, it's been blacks here and all across the railroad track.
The Henrys used to own the property over there.
The gays owned the property over there.
Maybe had they come here from Africa or do you know?
Just came from parts of America?
Do you remember the Blue Bonnet Motel?
It was a blue top and a blue bonnet.
I just saw a reference to it, but it was here.
It was right up here on the right.
And that's where people stayed who came to... White.
Well, could you really... See, this is something I'm not familiar with, segregation.
Because, you know, in the generation I grew up in, there was such a push...
LBJ presidency to make sure that everybody was treated equal.
But was it something that was very distinct here, the difference between black and white?
Not too distinct on the campus.
Educated people, white people, you have no trouble.
It's the poor white man that gave you trouble.
Were there poor white men living around here that gave you trouble?
No, it wasn't too much trouble we had.
Everybody got along like brothers and sisters.
There was no fighting that I can recall, or no arguments that I can recall.
But basically, the trouble comes in when you have the poor white class living with the black.
There was some poor whites lived on the campus then.
All I want are professors and things.
And they would say some snotty things, but that's life.
Some of them say it now.
You were talking about the trolley.
You would take the trolley to school and back each day?
Oh yes, I went by the nickel and dime.
Where did you get on it and where did it take you?
And you could walk to school from there?
Was your high school also segregated?
Was it all a black school?
Since you lived on campus, this is, you basically ate dinner at
On campus, I mean, did your parents bring food to the home and cook it there?
Well, my mother was a domestic, and if she didn't bring it from her job, I could go to the dining hall and eat.
I could go to the hospital and eat, because the people knew me.
And basically, she worked with people who lived on campus.
Wankler, just all of those people.
When did you and your family move off campus?
We moved over there in the Devil's Corner.
The place that you were just talking about?
And why were you, why did y'all move?
Was it, were the people, was every, were everybody moving off then?
These houses were just torn down.
Was your mother and father still working on campus though?
She and my father, I don't even much remember my mother and father being together.
But she was still working on campus.
Jackie Walker, Howard Bryson, Mr. Brayton, Mayfield.
Are you familiar with the Lincoln area, Lincoln School area?
Because there's a lot of black people that live there today, and I was curious as to, you know where Lincoln School is?
I really guess I can't explain it as to where it really is.
But do you know where Fairview Street is?
Did you hear of a community called Spring Green?
You may not have been in College Station at this time, but do you remember when College Station was incorporated into a city?
Not really, but I remember the first mail College Station had.
Why do you call him your white daddy?
Because I was just like a child of his, I told you.
It's because of me getting a college education.
Well, because everybody on campus knew me, and Mr. Tony Harrington, Mr. Fleming, Mr. Charlie Crawford, and numerous others contributed so much money.
And after I got my education, I sent the money back from San Francisco, and he distributed to each person the amount that they contributed.
Where did you go to school?
I went to school in California.
You went to school in California?
Well, I got a little old piece of paper.
But Mr. Lankford was responsible for providing...
For providing the money, and he got it from these group of men?
I went around and talked to each individual myself and told them what I wanted, asked if they would help, and they did.
And once you got your job, you sent back the money to these people?
Yeah, I sent it to my white dad, and he gave me that money back.
I was able to talk to Mr. Crawford, too.
I haven't seen Buddy since he was a little boy.
But his sister, he's got a sister who lives in Oakland, California.
Her husband and I work with the same company, Standard Oil Company of California.
I went to see her and I've been to her home and seen her kids.
Anyway, I guess, were you here when College Station became a town?
I mean, it wasn't just, you know, just being a boy at a store up there.
That was years and years ago.
Right along in there where, I don't know what's there now.
Yes, at Northgate by the post office, sort of down to the right.
Do you remember anything, any rivalry between Brian and College Station?
What are you referring to, Riley?
Well, Bryan, I believe, wanted to incorporate College Station into their own town.
And College Station wanted to be its own town.
They wanted to be College Station.
Well, to my idea, I think College Station is more sophisticated than the peoples in Bryan.
They know they've got to educate most educated peoples here than they have in Bryan.
And so they wanted to be counted as one instead of two, you know.
College Station, College Station, Brian's one.
Because if it wasn't College Station, there wouldn't have been any Brian.
Nothing but, well, farmers bringing their cotton in there.
And College Station, look what they was doing.
Because you see, at the laundry, maybe 100 black women were working there and some white, but they was getting $45 a month, five days a week.
The janitors, those fellows there, they was getting $45 a month.
So the college was supporting these people and providing them an occupation?
This man here wasn't, and this one wasn't.
But all the rest of these people were living in Weldon or Bryant.
So the college did support them then?
During the summer when school was out, they'd have those big vats.
You know what a bed bug is?
They'd have to dip all of those bugs in that creosote or whatever it was to kill those bed bugs.
You see, the books have springs on them.
Oh, you're talking about the beds that are on campus in the dorms?
They would have to, during the summertime, put them in?
You turn the light on, they line up like soldiers.
You're saying that the beds in the dorms were like that?
And so you would treat him each summer, is that right?
